, 

34

). In the nymph, 
1
) presence of dark macula on all femora; 
2
) head capsule broadly expanded apically with lateral concavity in males and females (although concavity weaker in females); 
3
) gills 
1
without fibrilliform threads (

Fig. 
17

); 
4
) protuberance in basal third of gills 
2–6
(

Figs. 
18, 19

, 

32

), and 
5
) claws with 
3–4
small denticles. The dorsal color pattern of abdomen and the presence of setal tufts posterior to the eyes would also appear to characterize the new species, but this suggestion is based only on published figures and the setae may have been previously overlooked.
